places.generalDescription: Perched on a hill overlooking the Johor Strait, Sultan Abu Bakar Mosque is a magnificent historical landmark in Johor Bahru. Built in 1900 over an eight-year period, it boasts a unique blend of Victorian and Moorish architectural styles. The mosque's exterior features traditional Malay design with a hint of Victorian influence, while its interior is adorned with white marble and showcases a charming mix of Victorian and Moorish elements.

sources.snippet: The Sultan Abu Bakar Mosque is a protected heritage monument that was constructed in the late 1800s. The entire structure boasts detailed Victorian architecture that will make you feel as if youâ€™ve stepped back in time as you explore the grounds. The mosque also sits on a hilltop that overlooks Singapore and the straits of Johor.

places.generalDescription: Johor Zoo, formerly known as Kebun Binatang, is a historic animal park established in 1928 by Sultan Sir Ibrahim of Johor. It was initially a private royal garden before opening to the public in 1962. With an entrance fee of RM2 for adults and RM1 for children, visitors can encounter approximately 100 species of animals including gorillas, elephants, lions, flamingos, snakes, birds and more.

sources.snippet: The Johor Zoo is said to be the very first zoo in Asia, having been established in 1928 by the late Sultan of Johor. It may not be as big as the Zoo Negara in KL, but this local zoo has its own merits that are enough to bring in a daily stream of visitors. And for only RM2/pax, itâ€™s an affordable activity where you can relive your schooling days from when kids would go on field trips to the zoo.

places.name: Johor Zoo

reviews.text:
A compact zoo offering surprising variety and fantastic hands-on experiences at a very affordable price. Perfect for a budget-friendly family outing of 2-3 hours.

RM10 for adults and RM5 for kids/seniors is incredibly reasonable. You definitely get more than your money's worth. Right at the entrance (Zone 1), you're welcomed by parrots and cockatoos you can actually touch and take selfies with!They even had snakes here too. This was a major highlight and a unique, memorable experience.
Despite its smaller size, we saw a satisfying range including elephants, chimpanzees, lions, tigers, the unique Malay tapir, camels, hippos, monkeys, and various birds spread across the zones

It's a fun place to visit with your family with an affordable ticket price. Not really a big place but you can see a lot of animals (which were put in a rather small confined space). I believe they were well fed because of their sizes. However during my visit, there were a lot of displays that were closed for renovation. Limited parking space, and please prepare a lot of water to drink.

You also can visit a newly opened botanical garden neighboring the zoo.

It was an unplanned visit to Zoo Johor during last weekend which turned up to be an incredible family trip for my 1y daughter.

1) TICKET
I just bought up the ticket via their official website the night before. And guess what, the website is exceptionally convenient. I finished my booking just within 5 minutes. It cost RM10/adult, RM30/foreigner and free for infant <2y. The idea of QR code is also obviously easier and faster access. As the cost given, they are very strict to see your honesty and will ask for your identification card & passport prior entrance. Don't forget to bring yours!â˜ðŸ»

2) THE ANIMAL EXPERIENCES
It is a compact but still a fun to visit zoo! Most might say the zoo is small compared to other zoo. Yes, I will not denied it. But maybe because of the age (not so old ðŸ˜Œ), it makes the journey shorter & less tiring even under the scorching sun AND carrying your 1y+ daughter all along. Even though they have less variation of animals, kids always happy whenever they watch animals. Hippopotamus is my fav one.ðŸ¦› Sadly, there was no giraffe at that time. Sometime, they have elephant show too. We managed to catch a memory with the birds.

3) THE TRAIL
It's a 50-50 stroller friendly. 50% of the trail are accessible by stroller/tricycle especially the first trail over your right when you enter. Meanwhile, the other 50% will be a challenge to all parents as we need to climb the stairs, mainly over the tiger,lion,bear area. No tips. Just endure it!ðŸ™ˆ

4) FOOD
Yeah, the zoo is friendly to outside food! Inside the zoo, only vending machines available. Along the parking area, they provide foodtrucks too. Buckle up some food and water from home if you want to save up. After strolling, you can shade under a 'picnic' area beside the playground and enjoy your food.

5) PARKING
Very limited along the main road area. It depends on your luck. However, there is a free shuttle bus provided from Kota Jail's parking (if I'm not mistaken). Sorry, I have limited info since I managed to get a parking along the road.ðŸ¤­

Have a pleasant experience in Zoo Johor!

places.generalDescription: B5 Johor Street Market, located in Johor Bahru, is a cultural hub where local communities come together to enjoy daily performances and festive attractions. The market offers a wide range of traditional Malaysian and Johorean cuisines through its F&B kiosks and food trucks. Additionally, it provides a unique retail experience with outlets spanning across fashion, IT & telecommunication, gifts, and souvenirs.

sources.snippet: Think of B5 Johor Street Market as a permanent bazaar that lets you patronise your favourite food stall and get good bargains all year round. Image credit: AKU Sis Lin. Youâ€™ll notice that most of the food stalls here offer signature Johorean delights such as laksa and satay, so itâ€™s a one-stop centre to check off all the local food you need to try here too.

sources.shortName: 52 Things To Do In JB: Theme Parks, Photo Spots & More

places.name: B5 Johor Street Market

reviews.text: Went there on weekdays. Chill place and variety of food that can munch. Thrifty stall that you will hop around. For your info, the food truck fully operate at 630pm.

While the market can be crowded during this Hari Raya festive, this adds to its charm.  It's a place where you can rub shoulders with locals, observe their daily routines, and experience the authentic heart of Johor Bahru.  The prices are generally reasonable, and bargaining is often expected and encouraged, adding another layer of engaging interaction to the shopping experience.

However, be prepared for a sensory overload.  The sights, sounds, and smells can be intense, and the narrow walkways can feel cramped at peak times.  Navigating the market requires patience and a willingness to embrace the lively chaos.

Overall, Johor Street Market is a must-visit for anyone seeking an authentic and immersive cultural experience. It's a place where you can discover unique treasures, savor delicious street food, and soak up the vibrant energy of a truly unforgettable marketplace.  Just remember to wear comfortable shoes and embrace the adventure!
A nice place to spend an evening browsing apparels n accessories. Nice street food to go shopping too. You can find pretty good deals here.

places.generalDescription: The Johor Ancient Temple, dating back to the 19th century, is a place of worship dedicated to five ancient deities and adorned with intricate and colorful decorations. It stands as one of the oldest temples in Johor Bahru, symbolizing unity among five ethnic Chinese groups. Despite being surrounded by modern skyscrapers, the temple reflects Johor's commitment to preserving tradition amidst progress.

places.name: Johor Ancient Temple

reviews.text: You can enter free of charge, it's my first time in a temple and i enjoyed seeing this cultural and historical place

Free admission.
Old Chinese Taoist temple with popular Chinese deities.

On the left hand side of the building, it houses the Buddhist's Guan Yin Bodhisattva ( è§‚éŸ³è©è¨ï¼‰; who is an enlightened person ( not a god/ deity ).
He is a Teacher of Compassion, who is often mistakenly called the Goddess of Mercy.

On the right hand side of the building, you will see some artefacts and read about the history of the temple.

The Johor Ancient Temple is a beautiful and historic spot right in the heart of Johor Bahru. It's amazing how this temple has stood the test of time, surrounded now by modern buildings, yet still retaining its charm and cultural significance.

The temple is small but rich in history, with its intricate architecture and well-preserved artifacts. It's a peaceful place to visit, and you can feel the deep connection it holds for the local community.

Definitely worth stopping by if you're in the area, especially if you enjoy exploring cultural landmarks. It's a nice escape from the hustle and bustle of the city!

places.generalDescription: Skyscape Johor Bahru is an exhilarating aerial entertainment space located at Menara JLand. The main attraction is the glass-bottom Sky Bridge, offering stunning views of Malaysia and Singapore from a height of 149 meters. Visitors can also enjoy virtual reality experiences, explore the multi-sensory LED Tunnel, and engage in interactive floor games. Additionally, there's a mini-theatre for film enthusiasts.

sources.snippet: Admire the buildings and feel like you are on cloud nine while at Skyscape. Opened in 2019, the glass rooftop deck on the 34th floor of Menara JLand. If you are not Malaysian, the entrance fee is RM38(~S$11.83) for adults, RM28(~S$8.71) for children, and RM33 (~S$10.27) for seniors.

places.name: Skyscape Johor Bahru

reviews.text:
There are 2 areas - indoor and outdoor. Indoor one heads to the north with city view, outdoor heads to Singapore and some city sights. Outdoor area is pretty small, but has cool views indeed. It has glass barriers and handrails, but they are not tall and do not mess with the view!
It's a good variant to look out the city in short time. Guess the views can be interesting in dark too.
One thing was strange only - I couldn't buy ticket by cash, online only )

Had a great experience here during my trip in Johor! The city view was absolutely amazing! Johor has a very clear sky during that day, the ticket is affordable and I suggest you to buy it in advance to avoide the long queue. Besides the skyscape and city view, you can also play several games in order and watched the Johor tourism video inside the office. The minus was I almost got lost to find the location, I asked the Grab driver they seemed wasn't acknowledge it. But besides that thing, I really enjoyed here so much.

For someone who is afraid of heights like me but wants to have a feel and try conquer their fears, this is it. Unlike other similar attractions that offers 360 degrees view while walking on never ending glass floor, this Skyscape will only take you about few steps from entrance to exit. With high glass wall panel that protects you from feeling falling over and high winds, you can safely overcome those fears and at least once in your life gather those guts to walk those glass floors. Just dont look down, if you must, then take a peek. Like me. That said, online booking must be made first in advance. After receiving your booking confirmation and QR, head down to Menara JLand and their friendly staffs will assist you from there.

reviews.text: One of the best places to do hiking in JB area, many wonderful trails to explore here, easy to intense trails available hereâ€¦..best to start your day here
We hike 11km around the lagoon. Recommended for new hikers too. A few climbs but easy with ropes. Many IG spots. The green corridor is pretty too. We shared the paths with many mountain bikes.

It's an okay hiking area - probably a disused old quarry, and the top there is a viewpoint and the lake is rather pretty.  follow your route through Strava.  it's not unsafe and there is a path, just that it's a bit of a pity that the trees in the plantation nearby are now felled and the land is barren.
